snippet.textDisplay:
A bit of a double edged sword there. I think the offer was greedy, it was a good starting point but should have been negotiable. It's true that the Dragons can rocket a product to success but it's also true that he's already put himself in a position of advantage.
What was the right thing to do?
He was confident about his patent and confident about the breweries offer, and once he had a deal he would no longer need the Dragons....even if he paid Theo 50k for consultancy he wouldn't lose 40& of his business.
As long as he pulls off this brewery deal, he made the right choice.

snippet.textDisplay:
Very bad negotiating tactics. If he knew he was going to stand firm on his 30% offer, he should not of asked so lightly if the dragons would "consider" the drop. He should of firmly made his position clear as to put the ball in the dragon's court.

A lot of these episodes the dragons and entrepuners are miles away in terms of meeting for a deal. However on this episode in particular, it is clear there was less than a hair strand standing in the way. With the facial expressions at the end from the dragons, it is clear they interpreted this guy as desperate for a deal, hence they did not budge. Sadly was just a poor negotiator

snippet.textDisplay:
However, to be fair, it actually is a really good idea. Soda can holders exist, to keep cans on their side so they roll out as you take one. Icecube trays exist so you can easily make and hold ice. My family has a butter stick holder, which you can press the base and slide the stick out at measured intervals so you can cut proper segments off.

This idea actually is very well thought through and absolutely will be bought.

10/10, I don't drink alcohol but fantastic design
